<br>
Thats not really the interesting deviation though. The interesting deviation is that of the underlying data - not the sample means.<br>
<br>
I would say that the easier way to make a confidence interval would be through computationally sampling from a distribution that resembles the one observed in the data. Sample the 500 hits say 10000 times and then compare the distribution of the 10k sample means to the observed sample means. That way you could get an alpha level stating if these sample means are significantly different or the difference could just be due to variance.<br>
<br>
Maybe I will do just that tomorrow if I get the time. <br>
<br>
