All the standard deviation will show you anyway is the distribution of your data.  There is PLENTY of data there to draw conclusions without getting into doing deviations the super-long way. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=remfdatroll@thesteelwarrior>Remf da Troll</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>/cons RED</span><br>  Posts: 344<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/3/03 2:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3094.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   a slightly different view...</span><hr size=1> Hi all-<br>
<br>
First of all, very nifty data- thanks!  Here's a thought tho- while trying to reverse engineer something that's fairly complex, it's usually a bad idea to ignore any potentially useful information.  In this case, we've got some decent data about what the output/results look like, and some theories about why it works that way.  But nobody has really discussed HOW those results must have been generated.<br>
<br>
This next bit is only my opinion, but I think it's pretty reasonable...<br>
<br>
Basically, any calculations done for combat must be SUPER efficient algorithmically.  I.e. there aren't going to be tons of floating point operations and other &quot;expensive&quot; calculations... it's gonna be pretty granular (bit shifts, overlays, straight integer, other?), but FAST.  Any rounding done will be VERY crude, more likely truncated and/or least significant digits dropped.<br>
<br>
Why?  The individual zone servers have to do those melee hit/miss/proc/damage/etc. calculations for dozens or hundreds of players AND mobs over entended periods at the same time while still supporting all the &quot;other stuff&quot; going on.  They apparently use some pretty decent equipment, but it's still got a FIFO/instant event stack that has to handle EVERYTHING that is occuring instant by instant. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
So, in a nutshell- expect there to be discontinuities and such in the data, and not smooth distributions.  In fact, I'd be shocked (and very impressed) if the output was either linear OR normally distributed.  Things like standard deviations and the like are appropriate for gaussian distributions for example, but if it doesn't fit this experimental data don't be surprised. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Just some thoughts, figured it might help to consider the how in deciding the what and the why. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
RdT. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=1ludor>1Ludor</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 169<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/3/03 3:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3094.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: a slightly different view...</span><hr size=1> &quot;Heh. I give up. I guess people get deep seated ideas in their mind like &quot;If we cold just get 2000 AC we could push past the ATK cap of aow!!!&quot; so they discounted all of the parses done on exp level mobs in luclin.<br>
