<br>
That might be - but taking the deviation of the means the way you did says exactly nothing. <br>
<br>
Why? Because it doesnt at all take into account the size of the samples used - they could be 1 hit or millions of hits each. Thus, that devition you listed doesnt help us figure out if these results are actually significantly different or if they could just be results of the random fluctuation. <br>
<br>
<br>
Remf<br>
<br>
Thats actually why you use the method I described - because its only for the standard simple distributions you have known results/statistics to work with in a meaningful manner. <p>Mikar</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=phantron>Phantron</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 273<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/3/03 4:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3094.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Brutall's ac test</span><hr size=1> I'd like to know how you come up with 2100 AC at the expense of any amount of HP.<br>
